onaire]]<br>{{small|KO5 [[Vic Darchinyan]]}} }}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[The Ring magazine Upset of the Year#2000s|''The Ring'' Upset of the Year]]<br>{{small|[[Bernard Hopkins vs. Kelly Pavlik|UD12 Kelly Pavlik]]}}\n|years=2008}}\n{{s-after|after=[[Juan Carlos Salgado]]<br>{{small|KO1 [[Jorge Linares]]}} }}\n{{s-before|before=Floyd Mayweather Jr.}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[The Ring magazine Comeback of the Year#2010s|''The Ring'' Comeback of the Year]]\n|years=2010}}\n{{s-after|after=[[\u00c9rik Morales]]}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}\n{{s-bef|before=Roy Jones Jr.}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Boxing pound for pound rankings#The Ring|''The Ring'' pound for pound #1 boxer]]\n|years=May 15, 2004 \u2013 July 16, 2005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Floyd Mayweather Jr.]]}}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Carlos Monz\u00f3n]]<br>14}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Most successful world<br>middleweight title defenses|years=February 19, 2005 \u2013 ''present''<br>{{small|15th defense on February 2, 2002}} }}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Felix Sturm]]<br>12}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Most opponents beaten<br>for the world middleweight title|years=April 19, 2014 \u2013 ''present''<br>{{small|13th opponent beaten on April 14, 2001}} }}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[George Foreman]]<br>Age 45}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Oldest boxer to win<br>a major world title<br>Age 49\n|years=April 19, 2014 \u2013 present<br>{{small|Broke the record at age 46;<br>broke his own record again at ages 48 and 49}} }}\n{{s-inc|rows=2}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Oldest boxer to hold or unify<br>multiple major world titles<br>Age 49\n|years=April 19, 2014 \u2013 present}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Ring magazine Fighter of the Year}}\n{{Sugar Ray Robinson Award}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hopkins, Bernard}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:African-American boxers]]\n[[Category:Boxers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:International Boxing Federation champions]]\n[[Category:International Boxing Organization champions]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from New Castle County, Delaware]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:World Boxing Association champions]]\n[[Category:World Boxing Council champions]]\n[[Category:World Boxing Organization champions]]\n[[Category:African-American Muslims]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam]]\n[[Category:American male boxers]]\n[[Category:The Ring champions]]\n[[Category:World middleweight boxing champions]]\n[[Category:World light-heavyweight boxing champions]]\n[[Category:Lineal boxing champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the basketball player|Bernard Hopkins (basketball)}}\n{{short description|American boxer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name = Bernard Hopkins\n| image = Bernard Hopkins making a speech at the United States Capitol, Feb. 2014.jpg{{!}}border\n| caption = Hopkins at the [[U.S. Capitol]], 2014\n| realname = {{nowrap|Bernard Humphrey Hopkins Jr.}}\n| nickname = {{plainlist|\n*The Executioner\n*The Alien<ref>Rafael, Dan (October 27, 2013) [http://m.espn.go.com/extra/boxing/story?storyId=9886458&src=desktop&wjb Hopkins otherworldly in decision win]. ESPN.com</ref>\n*B-Hop\n}}\n| nationality = American\n| height = 6 ft 1 in\n| reach = 75 in\n| weight = {{plainlist|\n*[[Middleweight]]\n*[[Light heavyweight]]\n}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1965|1|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia]],<br>[[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| style = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total = 67\n| wins = 55\n| KO = 32\n| losses = 8\n| draws = 2\n| no contests = 2\n}}\n\n'''Bernard Humphrey Hopkins Jr.''' (born January 15, 1965) is an American former [[professional boxer]] who competed from 1988 to 2016. He is one of the most successful boxers of the past three decades, having held multiple world championships in two [[weight class (boxing)|weight classes]], including the [[undisputed champion|undisputed]] [[middleweight]] title from 2004 to 2005, and the [[lineal championship|lineal]] [[light heavyweight]] title from 2011 to 2012.\n\nHopkins first became a world champion by winning the [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] middleweight title in 1995. He would go on to compile 20 defenses against 17 boxers, with both those numbers remaining a record for the weight class. In 2001 he successfully unified the middleweight division by defeating [[F\u00e9lix Trinidad]] to win the [[WBA (Super)]], [[World Boxing Council|WBC]], [[The Ring (magazine)|''Ring'' magazine]], and lineal titles. A victory over [[Oscar De La Hoya]] for the [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] title in 2004 cemented Hopkins' status as undisputed champion, while also making him the first male boxer to simultaneously hold world titles by all four major boxing sanctioning bodies. In 2001, Hopkins was voted Fighter of the Year by [[The Ring magazine Fighter of the Year|''The Ring'' magazine]] and the [[Sugar Ray Robinson Award|Boxing Writers Association of America]]. In 2011, ''The Ring'' ranked Hopkins as third on their list of the \"10 best middleweight title holders of the last 50 years.\"<ref>Fischer, Doug. (September 30, 2011) [http://ringtv.craveonline.com/blog/169390-10-best-middleweight-titleholders-of-the-last-50-years?start=8 10: Best middleweight titleholders of the last 50 years | RingTV] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003125540/http://ringtv.craveonline.com/blog/169390-10-best-middleweight-titleholders-of-the-last-50-years?start=8 |date=October 3, 2011 }}. Ringtv.craveonline.com. Retrieved on August 5, 2012.</ref> As of March 2020, he is ranked by [[BoxRec]] as the seventh greatest boxer of all time, [[pound for pound]].<ref>[http://boxrec.com/en/ratings?r%5Bcountry%5D=&r%5Bdivision%5D=&r%5Bsex%5D=M&r%5Bstance%5D=&r%5Bstatus%5D=&r_go= Boxrec all time p4p rankings]</ref>\n\nAfter losing the undisputed title to [[Jermain Taylor]] in 2005 and failing to regain it in a rematch the same year, Hopkins achieved further success in 2006 when he moved up to light heavyweight, winning the [[International Boxing Organization|IBO]] and ''Ring'' titles from [[Antonio Tarver]] at 42 years of age. Two defenses of the ''Ring'' title were made before a loss to [[Joe Calzaghe]] in 2008. Three years later, Hopkins defeated [[Jean Pascal]] for the WBC and lineal light heavyweight titles,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/lheavy.htm|title=The Lineal Light Heavyweight Champions|publisher=The Cyber Boxing Zone Encyclopedia}}</ref> as well as regaining the ''Ring'' title. This made Hopkins the oldest boxer in history to win a world championship, at the age of 46, breaking [[George Foreman]]'s record set in 1994. Hopkins later broke his own record by winning the IBF light heavyweight title from [[Tavoris Cloud]] in 2013, and again in 2014 when he won the WBA (Super) title from [[Beibut Shumenov]], at ages 48 and 49, respectively.<ref>[https://www.sbnation.com/2013/3/9/4084758/hopkins-vs-cloud-live-results-round-12 Hopkins vs Cloud live results: Round 12 \u2013 Bernard Hopkins wins unanimous decision to become oldest world champ ever]. SBNation.com. Retrieved on November 20, 2013.</ref>\n\nNicknamed \"The Executioner\", and later \"The Alien\", Hopkins was known among observers for his longevity and ability to continue competing successfully at an advanced age. Widely considered one of the greatest boxers of the modern era, he was a highly strategic and defensive boxer known for carrying good speed and power along with [[counterpunch (boxing)|counterpunching]] skills. He credits mastering the boxing fundamentals and a great defense for his longevity in the sport. He was also a very seasoned fighter, being able to take advantage of a wide variety of situations in the ring and implement rough and dirty tactics while fighting on the inside or in a [[clinch fighting#In combat sports|clinch]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aH053p5IQg0</ref><ref>http://www.doghouseboxing.com/Benz/Benz041212.htm</ref><ref>http://www.secondsout.com/archive/anthony-evans/taylor-dirty-hopkins-is-no-great</ref><ref>http://www.boxingscene.com/kovalev-explains-why-bernard-hopkins-dirty-fighter--83715</ref>\n\nIn the last years of his active career, Hopkins also became a minority partner with [[Golden Boy Promotions]], with which he still remains post-career.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn to Bernard Hopkins Sr. and his wife Shirley, Bernard grew up with his family in the Raymond Rosen [[public housing in Philadelphia|housing project]] in [[Philadelphia]]. Hopkins turned to crime early in his life.  By the age of thirteen he was mugging people and had been stabbed three times. At seventeen, Hopkins was sentenced to 18 years in [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Graterford|Graterford Prison]] for nine felonies. While in prison he witnessed the murder of another inmate in an argument over a pack of cigarettes, but also discovered his passion for boxing. After serving almost five years, Hopkins was released from prison in 1988. He then decided to use boxing as an escape from his previous life, and converted to [[Islam]].<ref>Steve Bunce (November 11, 2001) [https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2001/nov/11/boxing.news The forgotten prince] Guardian. Retrieved on July 29, 2009.</ref> While Hopkins was leaving the prison for the final time, the warden told him he'd \"see [Hopkins] again when you wind up back in here\", to which Hopkins replied \"I ain't ever coming back here.\"<ref>Jake Donovan (July 15, 2005). [https://web.archive.org/web/20090107135444/http://www.thesweetscience.com/boxing-article/2375/still-waiting-bernard-hopkins-grow-old/ \"Still Waiting for Bernard Hopkins to Grow Old?\"] July 15, 2005.</ref> Later, Hopkins attributed his personal discipline to his experiences and time spent in [[State Correctional Institution \u2013 Graterford|Graterford Prison]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ringtv.com/363149-from-the-ring-magazine-bernard-hopkins-learned-discipline-in-prison/|title=From THE RING Magazine: Bernard Hopkins learned discipline in prison - The Ring|date=2014-11-06|newspaper=The Ring|access-date=2017-02-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Amateur career==\nHopkins completed his amateur career with a 95\u20134 record.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060714075527/http://boxing-records.com/palm/voirpalmaf.phtml?boxeur=hopkinbe.html Bernard Hopkins Amateur Record] at the BoxingRecords. Last updated : March 13, 2006.</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Middleweight===\n\n====Early career====\nHopkins immediately joined the professional boxing ranks as a light heavyweight, losing his debut on October 11, 1988, in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]] to Clinton Mitchell. After a sixteen-month layoff, he resumed his career as a middleweight, winning a unanimous decision over Greg Paige at the [[The Blue Horizon|Blue Horizon]] on February 22, 1990.\n\nBetween February 1990 and December 1992, Hopkins scored 21 wins without a loss. He won 16 of those fights by [[knockout]], 12 coming in the first round.\n\n====Hopkins vs. Jones I====\nHopkins met Roy Jones on May 22, 1993 for the vacant IBF middleweight title. Hopkins was out-pointed throughout most of the fight, en route to losing a unanimous decision. All three judges scored the fight 116\u2013112 for Jones.\n\n===Middleweight title===\nThe IBF came again knocking at Hopkins's door on December 17 of that year, matching him with [[Segundo Mercado]] in Mercado's hometown of [[Quito, Ecuador]]. Mercado knocked Hopkins down twice before Hopkins rallied late and earned a draw. It has been argued that Hopkins was also not properly acclimated to the altitude of nearly 10,000 feet.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last =Rafael\n  | first =Dan\n  | title =Can Jones be serious?\n  | work =ESPN\n  | date =January 15, 2008\n  | url =http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/blog/index?entryID=3197314&name=rafael_dan\n  | accessdate =August 23, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe IBF called for an immediate rematch, and on April 29, 1995, Hopkins became a world champion with a seventh-round [[technical knockout]] victory in [[Landover, Maryland]].\n\nIn his first title defense he defeated Steve Frank, whom he stopped in twenty-four seconds. By the end of 2000, he had defended the IBF title 12 times without a loss, while beating such standouts as [[John David Jackson (boxer)|John David Jackson]], [[Glen Johnson (boxer)|Glen Johnson]] (undefeated at the time), [[Simon Brown (boxer)|Simon Brown]], and [[Antwun Echols]].\n\n===2001 Middleweight Tournament===\nThe arrival of former [[welterweight]] and [[light middleweight]] champion [[F\u00e9lix Trinidad]] into the middleweight ranks set off a series of unification fights between major middleweight title-holders. The boxers involved in the tournament would be reigning [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] champion Bernard Hopkins, [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] champion Keith Holmes, [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] champion William Joppy, and F\u00e9lix Trinidad.\n\n====Hopkins vs. Holmes====\nOn April 14, 2001, Hopkins won a unanimous decision over [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] champion [[Keith Holmes (boxer)|Keith Holmes]] in New York City. Trinidad, however, knocked out Middleweight mainstay [[William Joppy]] in an impressive five rounds.<ref>{{cite news\n  | last =Boxing\n  | first =BBC\n  | title =Triumphant Trinidad stops Joppy\n  | work=[[BBC Boxing]]\n  | date =May 13, 2001\n  | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/1327842.stm\n  | accessdate =June 3, 2008 }}</ref> This led many to believe that F\u00e9lix Trinidad was simply too much and too strong for Hopkins.<ref>{{cite news\n  | last =Fans\n  | first =Boxing\n  | title =How far can Felix go?\n  | work=[[BBC]]\n  | date =September 9, 2001\n  | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/sports_talk/1529355.stm\n  | accessdate =June 3, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n====Hopkins vs. Trinidad====\n{{Main|Bernard Hopkins vs. Felix Trinidad}}\nThen, on September 29, 2001, [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] champion Trinidad challenged Hopkins for middleweight unification in [[Madison Square Garden]]. The fight was originally scheduled for September 15, but the [[9/11 attacks]] postponed it by two weeks.\n\nFor the first time in many years, Hopkins was an underdog in the betting, which led the confident Hopkins to place a $100,000 bet on himself to win the bout. (The $100K came from a sponsorship deal Hopkins had with online casino site Golden Palace; Hopkins even had the [[GoldenPalace.com]] website displayed on his back for the fight.<ref>[http://www.boxingfutures.com/sites/default/files/Bernard-Hopkins.jpg JPG image of Hopkin's back]. boxingfutures.com</ref>) During promotion for the bout, Hopkins caused huge controversy by throwing the [[Puerto Rico]] flag on the floor in press conferences in both [[New York City]] and [[Puerto Rico]], the latter conference leading to a riot in which Hopkins had to be run to safety from the angry mob.<ref>Manuel Suarez (July 12, 2001). [https://web.archive.org/web/20070420013919/http://latinosportslegends.com/2001/Trinidad_Hopkins_riot_in_PR-071201.htm Riot in Puerto Rico during a Trinidad-Hopkins press conference]. latinosportslegends.com</ref>\n\nDuring the fight, Hopkins was on his way to a lopsided decision victory when, in the 12th and final round, he floored Trinidad.  Referee Steve Smoger called a halt to the fight after Trinidad's father (who was also his trainer) entered the ring to stop the fight. It was the first loss of Trinidad's career, and it made Hopkins the first undisputed world middleweight champion since [[Marvin Hagler]] in 1987. 'The Ring' magazine and the 'World Boxing Hall of Fame' named Hopkins as the 2001 Fighter of the Year.\n\nHe defended the undisputed title six times. Hopkins bested [[Carl Daniels]] on February 2 surpassing Carlos Monz\u00f3n's division record of 14 defenses, 2002, by tenth-round technical knockout; [[Morrade Hakkar]] on March 29, 2003, by eighth-round TKO; [[William Joppy]] on December 13, 2003, by unanimous decision; and [[Robert Allen (boxer)|Robert Allen]] on June 5, 2004, also by unanimous decision.\n\n===Undisputed middleweight champion===\n\n====Hopkins vs. De La Hoya====\n{{Main|Bernard Hopkins vs. Oscar De La Hoya}}\nIn the highest-paying fight of his career, Hopkins fought six-division titleholder [[Oscar De La Hoya]] for the undisputed middleweight championship on September 18, 2004, in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]].  They fought at a [[catch weight]] of 158&nbsp;lbs, two pounds below the middleweight limit of 160&nbsp;lbs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2004/Aug-21-Sat-2004/sports/24590920.html |title=In ring, Hopkins will finally dictate |newspaper=reviewjournal.com |author=Kevin Iole |date=August 21, 2004 |accessdate=March 30, 2011}}</ref> Hopkins won the bout by knockout in the ninth round with a left hook to the body and thus became the first boxer ever to unify the titles of all four major sanctioning bodies.  At the time of the stoppage, Hopkins was ahead on two of the scorecards, with De La Hoya ahead on the other.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2004/more/09/19/delahoya.hopkins/index.html | work=CNN | date=September 19, 2004 | accessdate=April 26, 2010 | title=Body blow}}</ref> Hopkins earned a career high of $10 million and De La Hoya made $30 million.\n\nIn November 2004, De la Hoya invited Hopkins to join his boxing promotional firm, [[Golden Boy Promotions]], as president of its new East Coast chapter.\n\nAt 40 years old, an age at which most boxers are retired, Hopkins reached the middleweight record of 20 title defenses on February 19, 2005, against ranked #1 WBC contender [[Howard Eastman]], the European middleweight champion. Hopkins dominated the fight from start to finish, winning 119\u2013110, 117\u2013111 and 116\u2013112.\n\n====Hopkins vs. Taylor====\n{{Main|Bernard Hopkins vs. Jermain Taylor}}\n\nIn his next fight on July 16, 2005, Hopkins lost his undisputed middleweight championship to [[Jermain Taylor]] via a split decision. Hopkins started slowly but came on strong over the final four rounds. Many press row writers scored the fight for Hopkins.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last =Mulvaney\n  | first =Kieran\n  | title =Lacy, Corrales, Common Foe Joppy Predict Outcome\n  | work = ESPN\n  | date =October 1, 2005\n  | url =http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2243473\n  | accessdate =October 24, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Light heavyweight===\n\n====Hopkins vs. Tarver====\nFollowing his two losses to Jermain Taylor, Hopkins at 41 decided not to retire and made the decision to jump two weight divisions to face off against ''The Ring'' light heavyweight champion [[Antonio Tarver]] on June 10, 2006. Going into the fight, Tarver was a 3-to-1 favorite and had been the first man ever to TKO Roy Jones Jr.  Many now placed Tarver among the sports top competitors. He was constantly ranked in the P4P rankings. However, Bernard Hopkins picked up a lopsided unanimous decision, scoring 118\u2013109 on all three judges scorecards.\n\nAntonio Tarver also lost a $250,000 bet with Hopkins, after he failed to stop Hopkins in the first six rounds.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last =Rec\n  | first =Box\n  | title =Antonio Tarver vs. Bernard Hopkins Fight News/Stats\n  | publisher =BoxRec.com\n  | date =June 10, 2006\n  | url =http://www.boxrec.com/media/index.php?title=Fight:1066695\n  | accessdate =August 26, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n====Hopkins vs. Wright====\nOn July 21, 2007, at the Mandalay Bay Resort & Casino in Las Vegas, Hopkins defended ''The Ring'' light heavyweight championship against former [[List of undisputed boxing champions#Junior Middleweight|undisputed junior middleweight champion]] [[Winky Wright]]. During the weigh-in, Hopkins shoved Wright with an open-hand to the face, igniting a brawl between both fighters' entourages.<ref>{{cite news\n  | last =Willis\n  | first =George\n  | title =Hopkins, Wright Brawl at Weigh-in\n  | work =[[New York Post]]\n  | date =July 21, 2007\n  | url =http://www.nypost.com/seven/07212007/sports/hopkins__wright_brawl_at_weigh_in_sports_george_willis.htm\n  | accessdate =June 3, 2008\n  | url-status =dead\n  | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20081206033110/http://www.nypost.com/seven/07212007/sports/hopkins__wright_brawl_at_weigh_in_sports_george_willis.htm\n  | archivedate =December 6, 2008\n  | df =mdy-all\n  }}</ref> Hopkins was fined [[United States Dollar|$]]200,000 for instigating the brawl.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =Hopkins fined $200,000 for weigh-in scuffle with Wright\n  | work = ESPN\n  | date =August 17, 2007\n  | url =http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2979488\n  | accessdate =June 3, 2008 }}</ref> Hopkins prevailed with a unanimous decision victory by scores of 117\u2013111, 117\u2013111 and 116\u2013112.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last =Rafael\n  | first =Dan\n  | title =Hopkins keeps title with entertaining win over Wright\n  | publisher =ESPN.com\n  | date =July 23, 2007\n  | url =http://proxy.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2945004\n  | accessdate =June 3, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n====Hopkins vs. Calzaghe====\n{{Main|Bernard Hopkins vs. Joe Calzaghe}}\nOn April 19, 2008, at the [[Thomas & Mack Center]] in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], Hopkins lost [[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]] light heavyweight title to [[Joe Calzaghe]] via [[split decision]] (116\u2013111 and 115\u2013112 for Joe Calzaghe; 114\u2013113 for Hopkins). Hopkins started the fight well, dropping Calzaghe in the first round and using his ring savvy to confuse the challenger. Calzaghe did however quickly adapt to the style of Hopkins and caught up in the middle to later rounds using his superior hand speed and output volume, leading to a split decision win for the Welshman.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/7355823.stm|title=BBC SPORT {{!}} Boxing {{!}} Calzaghe rallies to beat Hopkins|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref>\n\n====Hopkins vs. Pavlik====\n{{Main|Bernard Hopkins vs. Kelly Pavlik}}\nOn October 18, 2008, Hopkins met middleweight champion [[Kelly Pavlik]] in a non-title fight at a catch-weight of 170&nbsp;lbs. Fans and pundits alike felt that knockout king Kelly Pavlik would become the first man to knock Hopkins out. Pavlik was a 4\u20131 betting favourite heading into the contest. On the night of the fight, Hopkins turned back the clock to produce a performance he claimed to be the best of his career winning a unanimous decision ''(117\u2013109, 119\u2013106, 118\u2013108)'' over the undefeated Pavlik.\nHopkins prepared for this fight in the late summer heat at his second home, Danny Hawk's \"World Famous\" Normandy Gym in [[Miami Beach, Florida]].\n\nDuring the [[Ricky Hatton]] vs. [[Manny Pacquiao]] media conferences before their fight on May 3, 2009, Hopkins stated he would be \"interested\" in a proposed fight with British super middleweight champion [[Carl Froch]].\n\nOn December 2, 2009, Bernard Hopkins fought in his home city of [[Philadelphia]] for the first time since 2003 beating [[Enrique Ornelas]] via 12-round unanimous decision ''(120\u2013109, 119\u2013109 & 118\u2013110)'' in what served as a tune-up bout for the 44-year-old Hopkins who had not fought since his October 18, 2008 12-round upset victory over undisputed middleweight champion [[Kelly Pavlik]].\n\nThe bout was supposed to be a tune-up for a scheduled March 13, 2010 rematch with [[Roy Jones Jr.]] The rematch was later postponed as a result of Jones Jr. falling to a first-round technical knockout loss to [[Australian]] [[Danny Green (boxer)|Danny Green]].\n\n====Hopkins vs. Jones II====\n[[File:Bernard Hopkins 2010.jpg|thumb|Hopkins in 2010]]\n{{Main|Bernard Hopkins vs. Roy Jones Jr. II}}\nHopkins and old foe Roy Jones Jr. agreed to fight in a rematch on April 3, 2010 at the [[Mandalay Bay Events Center]] in Las Vegas. The two boxers fought again 17 years after their first bout in 1993. Hopkins defeated Jones by a unanimous decision in a 12-round bout marred by illegal blows and a skirmish at the end of the sixth round involving ring entourage, the referee and security guards. Judges Don Trella and [[Glenn E. Trowbridge|Glenn Trowbridge]] scored it 117\u2013110 for Hopkins, while Dave Moretti favored him 118\u2013109. The Associated Press had it 119\u2013108, scoring 11 of 12 rounds for Hopkins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=5054148 |title=Bernard Hopkins wins unanimous decision over Roy Jones Jr. \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=April 4, 2010 |accessdate=March 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe then challenged [[List of current world boxing champions|WBA Heavyweight Champion]] [[David Haye]] who had successfully defended his title against [[John Ruiz]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/8602743.stm | work=BBC News | title=Hopkins beats Jones and eyes Haye | date=April 4, 2010 | accessdate=April 26, 2010}}</ref> Following Hopkins challenge, Haye ruled out the fight stating Bernard was only looking for a payday.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/8603435.stm | work=BBC News | title=Haye dismisses Hopkins challenge | date=April 5, 2010 | accessdate=April 26, 2010}}</ref> Hopkins later stated his intentions to fight [[Lucian Bute]] following Bute's third-round technical knockout victory over [[Edison Miranda]]. [[Golden Boy Promotions]] also tried to approach retired boxer [[Joe Calzaghe]] for a potential rematch in 2010, but Calzaghe, who stated he no longer had the appetite, turned the offer down.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=28278 | title =Joe Calzaghe Turns Down Bernard Hopkins Rematch | last =Vester | first =Mark | work = | publisher =BoxingScene.com | date =June 3, 2010 | accessdate =June 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====Hopkins vs. Pascal I & II====\n{{Main|Jean Pascal vs. Bernard Hopkins|Jean Pascal vs. Bernard Hopkins II}}\nAt 45 years old, Hopkins fought [[Lineal championship|Lineal]]/WBC/The Ring light-heavyweight champion [[Jean Pascal]] on December 18, 2010 at the [[Colis\u00e9e Pepsi]] in [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]], Canada. The bout ended in a majority draw decision. Judge Steve Morrow had it 114\u2013112 for Hopkins, but was overruled by Claude Paquette (113\u2013113) and Daniel Van de Wiele (114\u2013114).<ref>{{cite news|last=Iorfida |first=Chris |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/pascal-hopkins-box-to-entertaining-draw-1.939892 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101220112516/https://www.cbc.ca/sports/pascal-hopkins-box-to-entertaining-draw-1.939892 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 20, 2010 |title=Pascal, Hopkins box to entertaining draw |publisher=Cbc.ca |date=December 19, 2010}}</ref> Following the controversy of the fight, WBC chairman [[Jos\u00e9 Sulaim\u00e1n]] sanctioned an immediate rematch.\n\n[[File:Pascal vs Hopkins 5081.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Hopkins (right) vs. [[Jean Pascal|Pascal]], 2011]]\nOn May 21, 2011, at the [[Bell Centre]] in [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]], Canada, Hopkins defeated Pascal by unanimous decision to capture the lineal/WBC/''The Ring'' light-heavyweight championships.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110113113734/http://news.yahoo.com/s/afp/20110107/sp_afp/boxusacanlightheavyhopkinspascal Hopkins-Pascal WBC title rematch ordered]. AFP. January 6, 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/early-results-from-montreal-21-84900#more-84900 Hopkins does it!!!] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524130321/http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/early-results-from-montreal-21-84900#more-84900 |date=May 24, 2011 }}. Fightnews.com (May 21, 2011). Retrieved on August 5, 2012.</ref> The official scores were 115\u2013113, 116\u2013112 and 115\u2013114.<ref>{{cite web |last =LaBate |first =Chris |title =Bernard Hopkins Beats Jean Pascal To Make History |work = |publisher =Boxing Scene |date =May 22, 2011 |url =http://www.boxingscene.com/bernard-hopkins-beats-jean-pascal-make-history--39442 |accessdate =May 22, 2011}}</ref> With the win, Hopkins became the oldest man in the history of the sport to win a major world title, supplanting [[George Foreman]], who had previously held the distinction after his knockout victory over Michael Moorer.<ref name=\"Oldest champ\">{{cite web |last = |first = |title =Bernard Hopkins becomes oldest champ |work = |publisher =ESPN |date =May 22, 2011 |url =http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=6574889 |accessdate =May 22, 2011}}</ref> Hopkins won at 46 years, 4 months, 6 days, while Foreman was 45 years, 10 months. After the bout, ESPN columnist Dan Rafael stated: \"Bernard Hopkins already had lived several boxing lifetimes, but he was born yet again in Saturday's decision over Jean Pascal, becoming the oldest champion in history.\"<ref name=\"Oldest champ\"/>\n\n====Hopkins vs. Dawson I & II====\n{{Main|Bernard Hopkins vs. Chad Dawson}}\nHopkins told the world of boxing that his next fight was going to be against former champion [[Chad Dawson]]. They fought on October 15, 2011. Hopkins lost via TKO for being unable to continue after injuring his shoulder when Dawson threw him off of his back.\n\nAfter an investigation by the WBC following a protest filed by [[Oscar De La Hoya]], the WBC ruled that Dawson intentionally fouled Hopkins and returned the belt to Hopkins. ''The Ring'' magazine also decided to continue to recognize Hopkins as their champion pending the California State Athletic Commission's ruling on a protest filed on behalf of Hopkins.<ref>[http://ringtv.craveonline.com/blog/169724-ring-light-heavweight-belt-wont-change-hands-pending-appeal RING light heavweight belt won't change hands pending appeal | RingTV]. Ringtv.craveonline.com. October 18, 2011.</ref>  Also on December 13, California State Athletic Commission (CSAC) has ruled that the decision will be overturned to a no-contest upon official review and the testimony of referee of the bout, Pat Russell.<ref>Rosenthal, Michael. (December 14, 2011) [http://ringtv.craveonline.com/blog/170703-california-commission-rules-hopkins-dawson-fight-no-decision California commission rules Hopkins-Dawson fight 'no-decision' | RingTV]. Ringtv.craveonline.com. Retrieved on August 5, 2012.</ref>\n\nA rematch with Dawson was set for April 28, 2012. Hopkins lost the bout via majority decision. Hopkins would not fight again in 2012, making it the first calendar year since 1989 that he did not win a fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/apr/29/bernard-hopkins-chad-dawson-live-boxing|title=Chad Dawson beats Bernard Hopkins - as it happened|last=Parker|first=Graham|date=2012-04-29|website=the Guardian|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref>\n\n====Hopkins vs. Cloud====\nHopkins would make his return to the ring on March 9, 2013 at the [[Barclays Center]] in [[Brooklyn]], against IBF Light Heavyweight Champion and ''Ring'' No. 2 ranked Light Heavyweight, [[Tavoris Cloud]]. Hopkins broke his own record becoming the oldest man in the history of the sport to win a major world boxing title, by defeating Cloud by unanimous decision.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/9035886/bernard-hopkins-win-vs-tavoris-cloud-shows-mastery-craft|title=Hopkins win shows mastery of craft|newspaper=ESPN.com|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref>\n\n====Hopkins vs. Murat====\nHopkins defended the IBF Light Heavyweight Championship against [[Karo Murat]] on October 26, 2013. The mandatory title defense was originally scheduled for July 13, 2013, but was later postponed due to visa issues for Murat. In the meantime, the IBF originally made [[Sergey Kovalev (boxer)|Sergey Kovalev]] Hopkins's new [[mandatory challenger]], but Kovalev instead faced and beat then WBO champion [[Nathan Cleverly]] to win the title, so Murat was reinstated as the IBF mandatory challenger and the bout was rescheduled for October 26, 2013.<ref>[http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/sport/story/223347.html Bernard Hopkins to fight Karo Murat on October 19 | Boxing News]. ESPN.co.uk (July 21, 2013). Retrieved on November 20, 2013.</ref> Hopkins won by unanimous decision with two scores of 119\u2013108 and one of 117\u2013110.<ref>Greisman, David P. (October 27, 2013) [http://www.boxingscene.com/bernard-hopkins-brawls-his-way-overcome-murat--71036 Bernard Hopkins Brawls His Way To Overcome Murat&nbsp;\u2013 Boxing News]. Boxingscene.com. Retrieved on November 20, 2013.</ref>\n\n====Hopkins vs. Shumenov====\nHopkins fought [[Beibut Shumenov]] in a championship unification bout on April 19, 2014, where Hopkins would be defending the IBF Light Heavyweight title and Shumenov would be defending the WBA Super and IBA Light Heavyweight titles, the latter not on the line for Hopkins. On fight night Hopkins knocked down Shumenov with a jab and followed with a powerful overhand right that nailed Shumenov on the side of the head and dropped him with only less than two minutes left in the round. Hopkins won by split decision with scores of 113-114, 116-111 and 116-111, becoming the oldest boxer in history to unify titles in a weight division.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/othersports/bernard-hopkins-49-unifies-major-world-titles-with-split-decision-win-over-beibut-shumenov/2014/04/20/75d3ded4-c82d-11e3-8b9a-8e0977a24aeb_story.html|title=Boxing: Bernard Hopkins, 49, unifies titles with split decision win over Beibut Shumenov|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=April 20, 2014|accessdate=April 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Hopkins vs. Kovalev====\n\nShortly after [[Sergey Kovalev (boxer)|Sergey Kovalev]] defeated [[Blake Caparello]] in a second-round knockout on August 2, 2014, Hopkins announced he would face the former in a match where his WBA Super and IBF titles would be on the line against Kovalev's WBO title. The match was signed after neither fighter could secure a contest with WBC and lineal champion [[Adonis Stevenson]]. The fight took place at [[Boardwalk Hall]] in [[Atlantic City]] on November 8, 2014 and was televised by HBO; this marked the end of a feud between Hopkins' promoter Golden Boy Promotions and the network which saw HBO cut ties with Golden Boy fighters.\n\nIn a one-sided fight, Hopkins was knocked down in the first round by Kovalev. Although he became the first fighter to take Kovalev past eight rounds, Hopkins lost every single round on all three judges' scorecards and took a 120-107, 120-107, 120-106 unanimous decision defeat, losing his titles.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/11845755/sergey-kovalev-defeats-bernard-hopkins-unanimous-decision | title=Kovalev defeats Bernard Hopkins | accessdate=November 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Hopkins called out [[Carl Froch]] again stating he would like to fight him in a farewell match, only for Froch to decline the offer calling it a \"lose-lose situation\". Hopkins also eyed [[James DeGale]] and [[Gennady Golovkin]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thaboxingvoice.com/bernard-hopkins-to-retire-in-2015/46024?var=no|title=Bernard Hopkins To Retire In 2015 - Tha Boxing Voice|last=O'Hara|first=Ryan|date=2015-06-04|newspaper=Tha Boxing Voice|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/31167739|title=Carl Froch: Bernard Hopkins fight would be a 'lose-lose situation'|date=2015-02-06|newspaper=BBC Sport|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref>\n\n====Hopkins vs. Smith Jr.====\nHopkins made an announcement confirming he wanted a final farewell fight before the end of 2016, which would be his first fight in over two years since losing to Kovalev in a lopsided unanimous decision. Hopkins also confirmed he would retire after this fight, whether it be at cruiserweight or light heavyweight, putting an end to his 28-year career.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingnewsandviews.com/2016/10/10/bernard-hopkins-next-fight/?|title=Bernard Hopkins Next Fight To Come Before End Of 2016|date=2016-10-10|newspaper=Boxing News and Views|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/bernard-hopkin-final-fight-golden-boy-president-gives-status--109670?|title=Bernard Hopkin's Final Fight: Golden Boy President Gives Status - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10621920/ring-legend-bernard-hopkins-to-retire-from-boxing|title=Ring legend Bernard Hopkins to retire after farewell fight|last=|first=|date=October 18, 2016|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=October 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA deal was made in October for Hopkins to fight American boxer [[Joe Smith Jr.]], who last fought Fonfara in June knocking him out in less than 3 minutes. The fight would be a HBO main event on December 17, 2016 at [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]] in [[Inglewood, California]]. Originally a co-feature with [[Orlando Salido|Salido]] vs. [[Takashi Miura|Muira]] until Salido injured his lower back and pulled out of the fight, making the Hopkins farewell the sole main event of the card. Later it was confirmed that, that another co-feature fight has been signed, as [[Oleksandr Usyk]] would be defending his WBO cruiserweight title against [[Thabiso Mchunu]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ringtv.com/468511-orlando-salido-hurts-back-off-dec-17-hbo-card/|title=Orlando Salido hurts back, is off Dec. 17 HBO card - The Ring|date=2016-10-17|newspaper=The Ring|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ringtv.com/468455-deal-place-smith-vs-hopkins-dec-17-hbo/?|title=Deal in place for Smith vs. Hopkins Dec. 17 on HBO - The Ring|date=2016-10-17|newspaper=The Ring|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/17817201/bernard-hopkins-close-boxing-career-bout-joe-smith|title=Hopkins to end boxing career with Smith bout|newspaper=ESPN.com|access-date=2016-10-18}}</ref> Both boxers weighed in at 174 pounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/hopkins-smith-weigh-174-smith-this-common-man-beats-his-ass--111825|title=Hopkins, Smith Weigh 174; Smith: This 'Common Man' Beats His Ass - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|access-date=2016-12-16}}</ref>\n\nHopkins did not contact trainer [[Naazim Richardson]] to train him for his final bout, instead having Kovalev's trainer [[John David Jackson (boxer)|John David Jackson]], a former boxer whom Hopkins defeated in 1997, train him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2016/11/30/13794220/bernard-hopkins-gets-new-trainer-for-final-fight|title=Bernard Hopkins gets new trainer for final fight|last=|first=|date=November 30, 2016|website=|publisher=|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn fight night, in front of a 6,513 crowd, Hopkins lost to Smith via TKO when he was knocked out of the ring in the 8th round and failed to make it back into the ring as referee Jack Reiss made a 20 count. Smith Jr. outboxed Hopkins through most of the first seven rounds, then,  in the 8th round, Smith caught Hopkins in the corner and landed five shots to the head that knocked him out of the ring. Hopkins said he was hurt and couldn't get back in the ring. He insisted that he had been pushed out of the ring, but replays showed it was not a push. Hopkins said to HBO in the post fight interview, \"He shoved me out of the ring. My ankle got twist when I fell out of the ring. I couldn't stand on my feet. If I wouldn't have been pushed out of the ring, I believe he was starting to fade... I can't believe they gave him a TKO. They can call it a no contest but not a loss. The momentum from his body pushed me. I went out like a soldier. I'm not in a denial.\" Hopkins sat down with HBO's [[Max Kellerman]] in the locker room after the fight and confirmed this would be his final fight. Smith Jr. retained his WBC International light heavyweight title. Hopkins' reported purse was $800,000, compared to Smith's $140,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/38356048|title=Bernard Hopkins beaten by TKO in final fight of career|last=|first=|date=December 18, 2016|website=BBC Boxing|publisher=|access-date=December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/videos/sports/boxing/2016/12/18/bernard-hopkins-knocked-out-ring-retirement-bout/95581282/|title=Bernard Hopkins knocked out of ring in retirement bout|last=|first=|date=December 17, 2016|website=USA Today|publisher=|access-date=December 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/18301362/bernard-hopkins-knocked-ring-joe-smith-jr-final-fight-ex-champ-career|title=Bernard Hopkins knocked out of ring by Joe Smith Jr. in final fight|last=|first=|date=December 18, 2016|website=ESPN|publisher=|access-date=December 18, 2016}}</ref> According to RingTV, the fight averaged 934,000 viewers, peaking at 1.035m on HBO.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ringtv.com/478102-million-turn-hbo-see-hopkins-final-fight/|title=More than a million turn to HBO to see Hopkins' final fight - The Ring|date=2016-12-20|newspaper=The Ring|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/hopkins-smith-averaged-934k-viewers-peaks-1035-million--111951|title=Hopkins-Smith Averaged 934K Viewers; Peaks at 1.035 Million - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|access-date=2016-12-20}}</ref>\n\n==Coaches==\nHopkins was coached by Philadelphia-based [[English \"Bouie\" Fisher]] from 1989 until their split in 2002 which resulted in Fisher taking Hopkins to court, claiming he was underpaid by $255,000. They re-united in 2003, but split again in 2005, again with Fisher claiming to be underpaid, this time to the tune of $200,000. [[Naazim Richardson]], Fishers long-term assistant took over as Hopkins' head coach from 2005. Fisher won the [[Eddie Futch-John F.X. Condon Award, awarded by the Boxing Writers Association of America, for Trainer of the Year]] in 2001. Bouie died aged 83 in June 2011.\n\n==Controversies==\nOn December 7, 2007, Hopkins and Calzaghe met face to face in the media room set up for the Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Ricky Hatton fight. Hopkins and Calzaghe began shouting insults and taunting each other, with Hopkins shouting, \"You're not even in my league! I would never let a white boy beat me. I would never lose to a white boy. I couldn't go back to the projects if I let a white boy beat me.\" Hopkins would later explain his comments, saying that it was not meant to be taken as a racial slur or a reflection of his feelings on white fighters, but simply said to create some hype for his fight with Calzaghe.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} On January 23, 2008, the fight was officially announced to take place on April 19, 2008, at the Thomas & Mack Center in Las Vegas. Hopkins lost the fight.\n\nIn late 2010, Hopkins suggested that African American fighters who possessed what he described as a \"slick\" inner-city style of fighting would be successful against Filipino boxer [[Manny Pacquiao]]. \"Maybe I'm biased because I'm black, but I think that this is what is said at people's homes and around the dinner table among black boxing fans and fighters. Most of them won't say it [in public] because they're not being real and they don't have the balls to say it. But I do think that a fighter like the [[Sugar Ray Leonard|Ray Leonards]] or anyone like that would beat a guy [like Pacquiao] if they come with their game. Listen, this ain't a racial thing, but then again, maybe it is. But the style that is embedded in most of us black fighters, that style could be a problem to any other style of fighting.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://offthebench.nbcsports.com/2010/11/19/bernard-hopkins-wonders-why-pacquiao-hasnt-fought-any-top-notch-black-fighters |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526023814/http://offthebench.nbcsports.com/2010/11/19/bernard-hopkins-wonders-why-pacquiao-hasnt-fought-any-top-notch-black-fighters/ |archivedate=May 26, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref><ref>http://thewellversed.com/2010/11/19/bernard-hopkins-says-pacquiao-ducking-african-americans-mayweather-would-beat-him/</ref>\n\nOn May 11, 2011, Hopkins questioned [[Minnesota Vikings]] quarterback [[Donovan McNabb]]'s racial credentials in a ''[[Philadelphia Daily News]]'' online article.  Marcus Hayes of ''The Philadelphia Inquirer'' reported that according to Hopkins, McNabb had a privileged childhood in suburban Chicago and, as a result, is not black enough or tough enough, at least compared with, say, himself, Michael Vick and Terrell Owens. Hopkins said, \"He's got a [[acting white|suntan]]. That's all... McNabb is [[House Negro|the guy in the house]], while everybody else is on the field... He's the one who got the extra coat. The extra servings... He thought he was one of them.\"<ref>http://articles.philly.com/2011-05-11/sports/29532616_1_rich-burg-bernard-hopkins-donovan-mcnabb</ref>\n\nIn late 2013 he again suggested that African Americans possess a \"slick\" style of boxing which is superior to other styles (presumably practiced by non-African Americans). \"The great Sugar Ray Leonard, right now, if he was boxing, the way that they want you to fight, the people that pull the strings of the puppet, he would be boring today. Ray Robinson \u2013 the great Robinson \u2013 would be boring today\u2026Because the feeders of the people that buy entertainment. They're being fed that if they duck, don't buy it. If they're slick, and they beat [their opponent] nine out of the 12 rounds, and the guy just can't hit him because they were slick and smart enough to hit and not get hit, 'He's not crowd-pleasing, he don't sell tickets.' Because they done fed the followers and they done fed [that] to the customers. The customers will drink anything that you give them if it's promoted right\u2026But when you take away the skill and you take away the slick, and you take away the boxing ability and say that's not entertaining, or that's not entertainment, then, to me, it's like trying to erase a culture that you know has dominated the sport way back then where you were slick. And I'm talking about black fighters. Yes, I said it\", said Hopkins.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxing.com/b_hops_claim_racist.html/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-12-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322032649/http://www.boxing.com/b_hops_claim_racist.html |archivedate=March 22, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=2\n|nc=2\n|ko-wins=32\n|ko-losses=1\n|dec-wins=23\n|dec-losses=7\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Age\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|67\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|55\u20138\u20132 {{small|(2)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Joe Smith Jr.]]\n|KO\n|8 (12), {{small|0:53}}\n|Dec 17, 2016\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{age in years and days|1965|1|15|2016|12|17}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|[[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]], [[Inglewood, California]], U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|For WBC International light heavyweight title}}\n|-\n|66\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|55\u20137\u20132 {{small|(2)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Sergey Kovalev (boxer)|Sergey Kovalev]]\n|UD\n|12\n|Nov 8, 2014\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{age in years and days|1965|1|15|2014|11|8}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|USA}} {{small|Boardwalk Hall, Atlantic City, New Jersey, U.S.}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Lost WBA (Super) and IBF light heavyweight titles;<br />For [[list of WBO world champions#Light heavyweight|WBO light heavyweight title]]}}\n|-\n|65\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|55\u20136\u20132 {{small|(2)}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|KAZ}} [[Beibut Shumenov]]\n|SD\n|12\n|Apr 19, 2014\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{age in years and days|1965|1|15|2014|4|19}}\n|sty