sdate=2 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131170744/http://www.eurostar.com/pdf/timetables/Continental_connections.pdf|archive-date=31 January 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seat61.com/eurostar-to-lyon-avignon-marseille.htm|title=Direct Eurostar to Lyon, Avignon and Marseille|author=Mark Smith|date=|website=www.seat61.com|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== North America ===\n==== United States ====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width= align=\n|+ \n! No\n! Origin City(Country)\n! Destination City(Country) \n! Train Name/No\n! Operator Name \n! Distance\n! Frequency\n! Running Time\n! Average Speed\n! {{abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n|1\n|[[Lorton, Virginia]] (United States)\n|[[Sanford, Florida]] (United States)\n|[[Auto Train]], 52/53\n|[[Amtrak]]\n|1376&nbsp;km\n|Daily\n|17hrs 30min\n|79&nbsp;km/h\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amtrak.com/ccurl/100/372/Auto-Train-Schedule-050712.pdf|title=Atlantic Coast Service |accessdate=August 19, 2012 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812162850/http://www.amtrak.com/ccurl/100/372/Auto-Train-Schedule-050712.pdf |archivedate=August 12, 2012 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Longest high-speed rail service==\nThe [[China Railway]] G403/4, G405/6 and D939/40 [[Beijing-Kunming high-speed train]] (2653&nbsp;km, 10 hours 43 minutes to 14 hours 54 minutes), which began service on January 1, 2017, is the longest [[high-speed rail]] service in the world.\n\nThe previous record-holder was the likewise Chinese [[Beijing\u2013Guangzhou\u2013Shenzhen\u2013Hong Kong high-speed railway]] at 2230&nbsp;km.\n\nEurostar previously held the record for its London to Cannes route, which set a record of 1421&nbsp;km non-stop high-speed service in 2006 (prior to the opening of [[High Speed One]]) \u2013 this was however not a regularly scheduled service.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609223354/https://www.eurostar.com/uk-en/about-eurostar/press-office/press-releases/2006/eurostar-sets-new-guinness-world-record-with-cast|title=Eurostar sets new Guinness World Record with cast and filmmakers of Columbia Pictures' The Da Vinci Code |date=17 May 2006|url=https://www.eurostar.com/uk-en/about-eurostar/press-office/press-releases/2006/eurostar-sets-new-guinness-world-record-with-cast|archive-date=9 September 2016|url-status=dead|website=Eurostar}}</ref> Currently, the record holders outside China are the Thalys service from Amsterdam to Marseilles, at 1265&nbsp;km in 7 hrs, 15 mins, and the Eurostar from London to Marseilles, at 1215&nbsp;km in 6 hrs, 26 mins.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Longest Train Journeys}}\n[[Category:Passenger rail transport]]\n[[Category:Transport-related lists of superlatives]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the trains with the longest routes|trains with the most wagons or carriages|Longest trains}}\n{{More citations needed|date = December 2014}}\n\nThis article lists longest passenger rail services that are currently scheduled and running directly between two cities. This list is not complete due to the complexity of various railway systems, its timetables and difference in schedule administration between countries. To keep the list simple, only services that are point-to-point direct between two cities are listed. Services that require railcar exchanges, coach changes, [[Shunt (rail)|shunting]] or station transfers are not listed.\n\n== Top 50 train services, by distance ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ \n|-\n! No\n! Origin<br/>(Country)\n! Destination<br/>(Country) \n! Train Name<br/>No\n! Operator Name \n! Distance (km)\n! No. of Stops\n! Frequency\n! data-sort-type=\"number\"|Scheduled running time\n!Ref.\n|-\n|1\n|[[Moscow]] (Russia)\n|[[Pyongyang]] (North Korea)\n|99 / 100\n|[[Korean State Railway]]\n|10267\n|157\n|Bi-Monthly\n|206 hrs (~8.5 days)\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pass.rzd.ru/static/public/en?STRUCTURE_ID=5125&layer_id=3290&refere